{"id":"1802.04378","submitter":"Thomas Barthel","authors":"Thomas Barthel and Jianfeng Lu","title":"Fundamental limitations for measurements in quantum many-body systems","comments":"9 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 121, 080406 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.121.080406","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.stat-mech math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Dynamical measurement schemes are an important tool for the investigation of\nquantum many-body systems, especially in the age of quantum simulation. Here,\nwe address the question whether generic measurements can be implemented\nefficiently if we have access to a certain set of experimentally realizable\nmeasurements and can extend it through time evolution. For the latter, two\nscenarios are considered (a) evolution according to unitary circuits and (b)\nevolution due to Hamiltonians that we can control in a time-dependent fashion.\nWe find that the time needed to realize a certain measurement to a predefined\naccuracy scales in general exponentially with the system size -- posing a\nfundamental limitation. The argument is based, on the construction of\n$\\varepsilon$-packings for manifolds of observables with identical spectra and\na comparison of their cardinalities to those of $\\varepsilon$-coverings for\nquantum circuits and unitary time-evolution operators. The former is related to\nthe study of Grassmann manifolds.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 12 Feb 2018 22:13:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-29"}
